    <!-- message -->
    <div align="left" id="post_message_533392">That makes sense to me, keeping it with other things to kill things for eatin'.<br />
<br />
Another thing about that drugs to guns analogy would be: a lot of those spree shooters - there don't seem to have been any major screaming warning signs. The more recent ones they seemed on the surface of it at least to not be too dangerous right up until they started shooting people. Then you have the ones who got their guns by cracking open the family gun safe. I'm not really sure that either solution that a lot of people propose: firmer gun control or everyone wears concealed guns all the time ... I'm not really sure that would fix this. At least not unless you went so far with firmer gun control as to approach like the English restrictions - which I think could never happen in the US, people simply wouldn't put up with that. To an outsider this seems like a much deeper complex issue involving culture, mental health care and expectations of gun owners.</div>
    <!-- / message -->
    
    
