</div>Quick-fire reply to the rest of those points:<br />
<br />
Mental health facilities and research need to be our focus.<br />
<br />
Teachers should not be armed, but there should be at least one or two trained professional armed guards (depending on the size of the school) on premise.  This would be a highly-visible deterrent for would-be shooters and, hopefully, rarely be needed to deal with threats.<br />
<br />
Guns should not be banned, but there should be more restrictive controls.  In addition a gun-safety course (with minimal actual training for use of guns beyond safety procedures) should be required in all hunting states and non-hunting states should have the option for the same course.<br />
<br />
It is a messed-up situation, but the key points taken away from this discussion should be a greater focus on mental health as well as compromise when it comes to gun control.<br />
<br />
<br />
<div align="center" style="margin:5px; margin-top:5px; ">
<table width="85%" border="0" align="center" cellpadding="5" cellspacing="0" bgcolor="#333333" class="bbcodeQUOTE">
  
  <tr>
    <td colspan="3" align="center" valign="middle">
	
	<div align="left"><b><div align="left" style="font-size: 12px; color: #999999; font-family: Verdana, Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif;"><strong>Zeno said:</strong></div></b></div></td>
 
	</tr>
  <tr>   
    <td width="30" align="center" valign="middle"><img src="/forums/images/openq.gif" width="30" height="30" ></td>
    <td>
		<div align="left" style="font-size: 12px; color: #999999; font-family: Verdana, Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif;">You seemed to miss the most important sentence: &quot;Whether there's a black market or not, the fact that it's an underground market still makes it a barrier for many if not most people&quot;.</div>
		</td>
    <td width="30" align="center" valign="middle"><img src="/forums/images/closeq.gif" width="30" height="30" align="right"></td>
  </tr>
</table>
</div>I didn't miss that question.  My point is that the barrier is minimal at best.  If you can get drugs you can almost certainly get guns from the same dealers or one of their immediate contacts.  Not to mention the fact that illegal items are constantly being sold through cleverly-worded Craigslist ads.  Guns would just be another one of those things.<br />
<br />
<br />
<div align="center" style="margin:5px; margin-top:5px; ">
