    <div align="left" id="post_message_533502"><div align="center" style="margin:5px; margin-top:5px; ">
<table width="85%" border="0" align="center" cellpadding="5" cellspacing="0" bgcolor="#333333" class="bbcodeQUOTE">
  
  <tr>
    <td colspan="3" align="center" valign="middle">
	
	<div align="left"><b><div align="left" style="font-size: 12px; color: #999999; font-family: Verdana, Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif;"><strong>Lilum said:</strong></div></b></div></td>
 
	</tr>
  <tr>   
    <td width="30" align="center" valign="middle"><img src="/forums/images/openq.gif" width="30" height="30" ></td>
    <td>
		<div align="left" style="font-size: 12px; color: #999999; font-family: Verdana, Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif;">Recently I keep seeing thing about how this isn't societies fault, we need individual responsibility. <br />
<br />
Mentally ill people are NOT responsible for their actions. They are mentally ill. We as a society failed those people.</div>
		</td>
    <td width="30" align="center" valign="middle"><img src="/forums/images/closeq.gif" width="30" height="30" align="right"></td>
  </tr>
</table>
</div>Damn.  I was hoping that this thread was going to die.<br />
<br />
I agree with you to a certain extent, but unfortunately the issue is not so black and white.<br />
<br />
Murder is abnormal behavior.  It is detrimental to society to kill a productive member of society.  (Killing unproductive members of society is just as wrong, but I'm sticking to the basics for our purposes.)<br />
<br />
By this standard anybody that commits murder is exhibiting abnormal behavior and is thus mentally ill.  Does this mean that nobody that commits murder is responsible for their actions?  Feel free to correct me if I'm wrong, but I don't believe that this is what you meant.<br />
<br />
The difficulty lies in where we draw the line between the people that commit these atrocities that should be punished for their actions and those who should be treated for these actions.  Or, to make things more complicated, also those who should be both treated and punished.<br />
<br />
To complicate things even further, is the treated person the same as the mentally ill person or does the therapy and/or medication alter their personality so thoroughly that they are no longer the same individual?  Once they've been treated and are within our definition of being mentally well should we punish them for their actions?<br />
<br />
I believe that the fault lies with both the individual and society as a whole.  Society should do their best to prevent and respond to mental illness, but when these measures fail we should do our best to determine the cause of the action and how to respond to it on a case-by-case basis.  If we determine that it was the individual at fault then they should be held responsible for it.<br />
<br />
There will likely never be a perfect system for this and certainly not in our lifetimes.  As a society it IS our responsibility to refine our knowledge so that we can address these problems the best that we can.</div>
    <!-- / message -->
    
    
