    <td width="30" align="center" valign="middle"><img src="/forums/images/closeq.gif" width="30" height="30" align="right"></td>
  </tr>
</table>
</div>Your logical problem comes from tying together &quot;abnormal behavior&quot; and &quot;mentally ill&quot;, and the legal definition of &quot;mentally incapacitated&quot;. Committing an abnormal behavior does not make one mentally ill. It might, at best, be a sign of mental illness; but in the mental health world a person who talks to Batman every night and hears an answer is not automatically mentally ill.<br />
<br />
Take, as an example, someone who talks to Batman everynight. Whole conversations. Disturbed? Probably. Suffering from something listed in the DSM? Almost definitely. &quot;Mentally ill&quot; with regard to the law? Not until they act in a manner that is illegal when they believe they are acting in a manner that is legal. Say the above person saw the Joker walking down the street, shooting people. In their mind, they would be justified in attacking the Joker (self defense or defense of others). They have commited a crime in actually attacking an unsuspecting passerby, but they are legally &quot;mentally ill&quot;.<br />
<br />
Now most murderers, on the other hand, know that their behavior is illegal. Most psychotic sociopathic type killers know it's illegal and take pleasure in that. They too suffer from DSM listed mental illnesses, but are not legally &quot;mentally ill&quot;.<br />
<br />
As for the so many people want to claim it's not society's fault, I refer to <a href="http://anarchistsoccermom.blogspot.com/2012/12/thinking-unthinkable.html" target="_blank">http://anarchistsoccermom.blogspot.c...thinkable.html</a> who has a child whom they suspect could end up hurting someone. But they can't get the police or mental health agencies to do much until he does hurt someone and is eligible for jail time. Society could help this child. Maybe.<br />
<br />
It's the far pendulum swing from the era where we just incarcerated everyone who seemed a little off; those days we ended up with otherwise perfectly functional members of society having their lives ripped away from them with ECT and lobotomies. And because we as a society don't look at mental health issues that often (how many people see a shrink as often as they see even an eye doctor) the pendulum is much slower swinging.</div>
