    <!-- message -->
    <div align="left" id="post_message_533515"><div align="center" style="margin:5px; margin-top:5px; ">
<table width="85%" border="0" align="center" cellpadding="5" cellspacing="0" bgcolor="#333333" class="bbcodeQUOTE">
  
  <tr>
    <td colspan="3" align="center" valign="middle">
	
	<div align="left"><b><div align="left" style="font-size: 12px; color: #999999; font-family: Verdana, Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif;"><strong>Kambic said:</strong></div></b></div></td>
 
	</tr>
  <tr>   
    <td width="30" align="center" valign="middle"><img src="/forums/images/openq.gif" width="30" height="30" ></td>
    <td>
		<div align="left" style="font-size: 12px; color: #999999; font-family: Verdana, Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif;">I think you're really watering down premeditated murder by categorizing it as merely an antisocial personality disorder...</div>
		</td>
    <td width="30" align="center" valign="middle"><img src="/forums/images/closeq.gif" width="30" height="30" align="right"></td>
  </tr>
</table>
</div>You're right, but you're missing the point that I was trying to illustrate.  The fact is that murder, no matter what the reason, is not the action of a healthy mind with the exception of being subjected to (real, not imagined) threats to the person's (or that of their family/friends/etc) well-being or similar coercion.  Whether it's caused by ASPD or another mental illness it is still an extremely abnormal behavior that is detrimental to the social organism.<br />
<br />
Remember that mental wellness is a relative term.  If it was normal for the majority of the people in the world to kill at least one person in their lifetime then murder would be a hallmark of mental wellness.  If a person didn't kill at least one person in their lifetime they would be seen as mentally ill by the standards of that imaginary society.<br />
<br />
Mental illness is identified as being a pattern of behaviors that varies from the norm and is harmful (in varying degrees) to either a single person or those that the person interacts with.</div>
