    <div align="left" id="post_message_533516"><div align="center" style="margin:5px; margin-top:5px; ">
<table width="85%" border="0" align="center" cellpadding="5" cellspacing="0" bgcolor="#333333" class="bbcodeQUOTE">
  
  <tr>
    <td colspan="3" align="center" valign="middle">
	
	<div align="left"><b><div align="left" style="font-size: 12px; color: #999999; font-family: Verdana, Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif;"><strong>Pearll said:</strong></div></b></div></td>
 
	</tr>
  <tr>   
    <td width="30" align="center" valign="middle"><img src="/forums/images/openq.gif" width="30" height="30" ></td>
    <td>
		<div align="left" style="font-size: 12px; color: #999999; font-family: Verdana, Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif;">The difficulty lies in where we draw the line between the people that commit these atrocities that should be punished for their actions and those who should be treated for these actions.  Or, to make things more complicated, also those who should be both treated and punished.</div>
		</td>
    <td width="30" align="center" valign="middle"><img src="/forums/images/closeq.gif" width="30" height="30" align="right"></td>
  </tr>
</table>
</div>Eh, a difficulty certainly does lie there but it speaks to a larger issue that is at the very foundation of our criminal justice system. What is the point of criminal justice? What is its goal?<br />
<br />
At the end of the day, it's simply to make the general public feel good, and so we run into issues like this because it has no aim beyond satisfying the current subjective mindset of nebulous and undefinable concepts such as &quot;justice&quot; and &quot;fairness.&quot;<br />
<br />
If we tried to actually fix these issues, without regard to making people feel vindicated or satisfying that thoroughly apelike part of our mind, we'd be treating this issue as any other medical problem. Criminality is a disease and it should be treated. Will this mean that sometimes you won't get to feel good to see someone who you believe deserves to suffer suffer? Certainly. I don't really give a **** about your feelings, though, and this is most reasonable approach that is actually in accord with fundamental secular societal values.<br />
<br />
There is no role for punishment, only treatment; and, for more complex crimes, deterrence through severe punishment (white collar crimes and other crimes where deterrence actually works--it almost never, ever works for murder).<br />
<div align="center" style="margin:5px; margin-top:5px; ">
<table width="85%" border="0" align="center" cellpadding="5" cellspacing="0" bgcolor="#333333" class="bbcodeQUOTE">
  
  <tr>
    <td colspan="3" align="center" valign="middle">
	
	<div align="left"><b><div align="left" style="font-size: 12px; color: #999999; font-family: Verdana, Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif;"><strong>Pearll said:</strong></div></b></div></td>
 
	</tr>
  <tr>   
    <td width="30" align="center" valign="middle"><img src="/forums/images/openq.gif" width="30" height="30" ></td>
    <td>
		<div align="left" style="font-size: 12px; color: #999999; font-family: Verdana, Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif;">To clarify, &quot;mental illness&quot; is a medical term.  &quot;Insanity&quot; is a legal term.  They have two separate definitions, but are not mutually exclusive.</div>
		</td>
    <td width="30" align="center" valign="middle"><img src="/forums/images/closeq.gif" width="30" height="30" align="right"></td>
  </tr>
</table>
</div>Yea, but they also aren't even remotely related conceptually, regardless of some probably large overlap.<br />
<br />
EDIT: I should add that I don't expect it to ever change in our society. It would require pretty much a new start from scratch. And, at the end of the day, even if it was possible all-be-it tough I still have no illusion that such a change could ever occur because fundamentally people are giant ****ing babies.</div>
