		<div align="left" style="font-size: 12px; color: #999999; font-family: Verdana, Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif;">I LOVE the irony of all of this. Not to stereotype but I would guess NRA members are generally conservative or libertarian. Both groups bemoan any sort of taxation which would be required to pay all those police salaries. And the libertarians would have a screaming fit about a police state with cops posted outside every school. <br />
<br />
So boils down to &quot;we have a plan we don't want to pay for&quot;.</div>
		</td>
    <td width="30" align="center" valign="middle"><img src="/forums/images/closeq.gif" width="30" height="30" align="right"></td>
  </tr>
</table>
</div>We have a passable system in place; if you are involuntarily detained for mental illness, you aren't supposed to be able to get a gun. Maybe if we phrase it as &quot;enhancing mental health funding&quot; while using it to make sure that the people who shouldn't have guns don't, and also getting them the help they need, maybe the NRA won't notice.<br />
<br />
No, that's probably too much to hope for. They'd whing about &quot;taxes helping those people not bootstrappy enough to not be depressed&quot; or something. After all, if they've worked in a dead end job at a dying coal mine or rail yard for 30 years and just lost their insurance and didn't kill anyone, how could someone who is &quot;just depressed about nothing&quot; actually do something like this. And I wish I made up that statement, but I've heard exactly that from otherwise rational people.</div>
    <!-- / message -->
    
    
