    <div align="left" id="post_message_533559"><div align="center" style="margin:5px; margin-top:5px; ">
<table width="85%" border="0" align="center" cellpadding="5" cellspacing="0" bgcolor="#333333" class="bbcodeQUOTE">
  
  <tr>
    <td colspan="3" align="center" valign="middle">
	
	<div align="left"><b><div align="left" style="font-size: 12px; color: #999999; font-family: Verdana, Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif;"><strong>Tivia said:</strong></div></b></div></td>
 
	</tr>
  <tr>   
    <td width="30" align="center" valign="middle"><img src="/forums/images/openq.gif" width="30" height="30" ></td>
    <td>
		<div align="left" style="font-size: 12px; color: #999999; font-family: Verdana, Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif;">Find a single place in the world that actually works. I'll give you the spoiler, you can't because one doesn't exist. Gun bans keep guns out of the hands of law abiding citizens and do nothing to deter criminals. So that bet of yours would be a losing one.<br />
<br />
I like many others here would fully support reasonable restrictions. The problem is the definition of reasonable varies wildly. I completely oppose outright bans because they don't work and never will work. I don't support actions taken around events like this because they are just kneejerk reactions based on hysteria. We do have a problem in America when it comes to violence. However guns aren't that problem and doing anything about them is tantamount to putting a band-aid on a severed limb. If you want to cure a disease, you have to target the disease, not lop off body parts hoping you get lucky. We have a very deep problem in this country with ignoring mental illness, not enforcing personal responsibility and executing true justice that is blind to status, color, sex etc etc.</div>
		</td>
    <td width="30" align="center" valign="middle"><img src="/forums/images/closeq.gif" width="30" height="30" align="right"></td>
  </tr>
</table>
</div>Australia, no mass shootings since their ban.<br />
<br />
That being said, I don't agree with a ban. <br />
<br />
The problem is a cultural thing so deeply ingrained within us as Americans it will never be fixed. <br />
<br />
WAY back when I was a sophomore in high school a kid walked into his home room put a gun to his head and killed himself. The Pearl Jam song Jeremy was inspired by the incident. In my English class we had to write an essay about why we thought this kid did and how we felt about it. Back then I was the tall, pimply, nerdy kid, who couldn't sit through a class without having my ears flipped or my books pushed off my desk. While writing the essay I remember some of my classmates laughing about this kid who had been bullied into taking his own life. I wrote in my essay that I understood where the kid was coming from, but if I were to ever bring a gun to school it wouldn't be to kill myself. I have no idea how I didn't end up in school counselors office after writing that essay. Looking back on it that teacher really dropped the ball.</div>
