    <div align="left">
	<hr align="left" width="100%" />

    <!-- message -->
    <div align="left" id="post_message_533572">I dont think anyone disagrees that during the American Revolution that arms were necessary. But the thing is, they were muzzle loading, black powder ignited muskets and &quot;pistols&quot;. And you know what, if we still only had those guns, Id probably say &quot;Sure! Keep em&quot;, the reason is because they do not lend themselves to mass firing rates.<br />
<br />
If you look up the Brown Bess it says that a highly trained rifleman would get a shot off about every 20 seconds, 3-4 a minute if you are lucky. I can unload a pistol as quickly as I can pull the trigger. On top of the rate of fire, the muskets of the era were highly in effective after 100m, todays rifles can fire at triple that distance. <br />
<br />
Yes, a society has the right to overthrow a tyranical government, as we have seen in recent years in other parts of the world. But in America, do we have a tyranical government? Sure people will spout that President Obama is a &quot;dictator&quot; but they are just chest puffing and spouting nonsense. In the &quot;civilized world&quot; I think we really have evolved past the necessity of firearms among the general populace. We dont even need militias anymore, we have a volunteer army and police service(I say volunteer because you choose to join up, they dont force you to serve).<br />
<br />
I feel a big problem with guns is, and this sounds weird, they are impersonal. Its easy to distance yourself from a victim if all you do is pull a trigger. It is very similar, and I am loathe to use this analogy, like a video game. I pull the trigger in a game, and pixels disappear. I dont know if they felt any pain, I dont have to feel their blood on my hands. Id be willing to wager that if you put a gun in a persons hand and asked them to pull the trigger they would be more willing to do it than if you put a knife/sword in their hand. A gun is a distance kill, pull the trigger, its over. A knife/sword is personal, you have to get close, you have to feel it plunge into their skin. Its much harder to do something when you need to be that personal. <br />
<br />
So yes, you can call me a Pollyanna, but I really do think that severely restrictings guns would solve some, not all, but some of our violence problems.</div>
    <!-- / message -->
    
    
    <br>
