    <td>
		<div align="left" style="font-size: 12px; color: #999999; font-family: Verdana, Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif;">By the way, as Australia has a population of 22 million and the USA of 311 million... shouldn't we statistically expect Australia to have proportionally fewer shootings? I don't mean &quot;expect&quot; like &quot;planning for them to have a certain amount&quot; but I mean when we are doing comparisons, shouldn't that affect the baseline?</div>
		</td>
    <td width="30" align="center" valign="middle"><img src="/forums/images/closeq.gif" width="30" height="30" align="right"></td>
  </tr>
</table>
</div>That's why they count it as murders per 100,000. So no actual population shouldn't have anything at all to do with the baseline.</div>
    <!-- / message -->
    
    
    <br>
<br>
<table width="100%%"  border="0" cellpadding="3">
<tr>
<td>


</td>
 </tr>
</table>
 

</div>
    </td>
  </tr>
</table>

